  "output": "## Test Coverage Analysis — jobsquare\n\n**Current state: 0%.** No test files, no test framework in `requirements.txt`, no `conftest.py`/`pytest.ini`. Every module below is completely untested. This is a good candidate for `pytest` + `pytest-asyncio` + `httpx.MockTransport` (httpx is already a dependency, so mocking transport requires no new library beyond the two I listed).\n\nSuggested layout: `tests/test_models.py`, `tests/test_filters.py`, `tests/test_store.py`, `tests/test_fetchers.py`, `tests/test_notify.py`, `tests/test_pipeline.py`, `tests/test_agent.py`.\n\n---\n\n### 1. `models.py` — `parse_posted_at`, `Job`\n\nHighest ROI: pure functions, no I/O, and `parse_posted_at` has three separate parsing branches (epoch-seconds, epoch-ms, ISO-8601) that are currently unverified.\n\n**Gaps:**\n- Millisecond vs. second epoch disambiguation (`>= 1e12` threshold) — untested at the boundary.\n- Negative/garbage numeric strings (`\"-1\"`, `\"abc123\"`).\n- Trailing `Z` normalization for pre-3.11 `fromisoformat` compat.\n- Naive ISO strings (no tzinfo) — should get `UTC` attached.\n- Empty string / `None`-like input → `None`.\n- Workday's `\"Posted 3 Days Ago\"` prose → must return `None`, not raise.\n- `Job.key` stability across title/location edits (dedup identity).\n- `Job.content_hash` — verify it changes when title/location/url/department change, and does NOT change when e.g. `posted_at` or `salary_range` change (those are excluded from the hash — worth locking that in explicitly since it's a deliberate design choice with no comment/test backing it).\n- `Job.to_row()` drops `raw`, includes computed `key`/`content_hash`.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_models.py\nimport pytest\nfrom datetime import timezone\nfrom models import Job, parse_posted_at\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"value,expected_year\", [\n    (\"1643241332430\", 2022),   # Lever ms epoch\n    (\"1643241332\", 2022),      # plain seconds epoch\n])\ndef test_parse_posted_at_epoch(value, expected_year):\n    dt = parse_posted_at(value)\n    assert dt.year == expected_year\n    assert dt.tzinfo == timezone.utc\n\ndef test_parse_posted_at_iso_with_z():\n    dt = parse_posted_at(\"2024-01-15T10:00:00Z\")\n    assert dt.tzinfo == timezone.utc\n\ndef test_parse_posted_at_naive_iso_gets_utc():\n    dt = parse_posted_at(\"2024-01-15T10:00:00\")\n    assert dt.tzinfo == timezone.utc\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"value\", [\"\", None, \"Posted 3 Days Ago\", \"not a date\"])\ndef test_parse_posted_at_unparseable_returns_none(value):\n    assert parse_posted_at(value) is None\n\ndef test_job_content_hash_ignores_posted_at_and_salary():\n    base = dict(source=\"gh\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng\",\n                url=\"https://x\", location=\"NYC\")\n    a = Job(**base, posted_at=\"2024-01-01\", salary_range=\"100k\")\n    b = Job(**base, posted_at=\"2025-06-01\", salary_range=\"200k\")\n    assert a.content_hash == b.content_hash\n\ndef test_job_content_hash_changes_on_title():\n    base = dict(source=\"gh\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", url=\"https://x\")\n    a = Job(**base, title=\"Eng I\")\n    b = Job(**base, title=\"Eng II\")\n    assert a.content_hash != b.content_hash\n\ndef test_job_key_survives_title_change():\n    a = Job(source=\"gh\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng I\", url=\"\")\n    b = Job(source=\"gh\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng II\", url=\"\")\n    assert a.key == b.key\n\ndef test_job_to_row_drops_raw_and_adds_computed_fields():\n    j = Job(source=\"gh\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng\", url=\"\",\n            raw={\"secret\": \"data\"})\n    row = j.to_row()\n    assert \"raw\" not in row\n    assert row[\"key\"] == j.key\n    assert row[\"content_hash\"] == j.content_hash\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `filters.py` — `match`, `filter_jobs`\n\n**Gaps:**\n- Word-boundary regex behavior: `\"go\"` should not match `\"mango\"` but should match `\"Go Developer\"`.\n- Case-insensitivity.\n- `exclude` takes precedence over `include` (a job matching both should be dropped) — this ordering is implicit in the code and untested.\n- Empty `include`/`exclude`/`locations` lists vs. `None` — code does `if include:` so `[]` behaves like `None` (no filtering). Worth a regression test since it's an easy off-by-behavior to break.\n- `locations` substring matching (`\"york\"` matches `\"New York\"`).\n- `cutoff` behavior when `posted_dt` is `None` (must be *kept*, not dropped) — this is a deliberate business rule with a comment; needs a test to protect it.\n- `filter_jobs` with `max_age_days` as string vs. float from YAML.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_filters.py\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\nfrom models import Job\nfrom filters import match, filter_jobs\n\ndef _job(**kw):\n    return Job(source=\"gh\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Engineer\",\n                url=\"\", location=\"New York\", department=\"Eng\", **kw)\n\ndef test_match_word_boundary_excludes_substring():\n    assert match(_job(title=\"Mango Developer\"), include=[\"go\"])  # matches \"Go\" boundary? check false positive\n    # \"go\" as \\bgo\\b should NOT match inside \"Mango\"\n    assert not match(_job(title=\"Mango Sales\"), include=[\"go\"])\n\ndef test_match_exclude_wins_over_include():\n    j = _job(title=\"Senior Manager\")\n    assert not match(j, include=[\"manager\"], exclude=[\"senior\"])\n\ndef test_match_locations_is_substring_case_insensitive():\n    assert match(_job(location=\"New York, NY\"), locations=[\"york\"])\n    assert not match(_job(location=\"Austin, TX\"), locations=[\"york\"])\n\ndef test_match_cutoff_keeps_unparseable_posted_at():\n    j = _job(posted_at=\"\")  # unparseable\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=1)\n    assert match(j, cutoff=cutoff)\n\ndef test_match_cutoff_drops_old_dated_job():\n    j = _job(posted_at=(datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=30)).isoformat())\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=7)\n    assert not match(j, cutoff=cutoff)\n\ndef test_filter_jobs_max_age_days_from_yaml_string():\n    j = _job(posted_at=datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat())\n    result = filter_jobs([j], {\"max_age_days\": \"7\"})\n    assert result == [j]\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `store.py` — `Store` (SQLite dedup)\n\nThis is the module with the most operational risk — your own memory notes flag **parallel worker collisions** as a known real bug class here (`jobsquare-parallel-worker-collisions.md`), and `next_seq`/`diff` are exactly the concurrency-sensitive code paths. This deserves the most new test investment.\n\n**Gaps:**\n- `diff()`: new job → inserted, appears in `new`; unchanged job (same `content_hash`) → not in either list, but `last_seen` still bumped; changed job (different hash) → appears in `changed`, row updated.\n- Schema migration path: opening a pre-`salary_range` DB (simulate by creating table without that column, then constructing `Store`) should add the column without failing.\n- `get_meta`/`set_meta` round-trip, and `set_meta` upsert overwrite behavior.\n- `next_seq`: sequential increments starting at 1; **concurrent callers must not collide** — this is the critical untested invariant given `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` is the whole point of the method.\n- `added_since`: boundary is strictly `>`, not `>=`; ordering by `first_seen, company, title`.\n- `count()`.\n- Context manager (`__enter__`/`__exit__`) closes the connection.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_store.py\nimport sqlite3\nimport tempfile\nimport threading\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport pytest\nfrom models import Job\nfrom store import Store\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef db_path(tmp_path):\n    return tmp_path / \"test.db\"\n\ndef _job(external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng\"):\n    return Job(source=\"gh\", company=\"acme\", external_id=external_id, title=title, url=\"\")\n\ndef test_diff_new_job_inserted(db_path):\n    with Store(db_path) as store:\n        new, changed = store.diff([_job()])\n        assert len(new) == 1 and changed == []\n        assert store.count() == 1\n\ndef test_diff_unchanged_job_not_reported_but_last_seen_bumped(db_path):\n    with Store(db_path) as store:\n        store.diff([_job()])\n        new, changed = store.diff([_job()])\n        assert new == [] and changed == []\n\ndef test_diff_changed_job_reported_and_updated(db_path):\n    with Store(db_path) as store:\n        store.diff([_job(title=\"Eng I\")])\n        new, changed = store.diff([_job(title=\"Eng II\")])\n        assert new == [] and len(changed) == 1\n        row = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT title FROM jobs WHERE external_id='1'\").fetchone()\n        assert row[\"title\"] == \"Eng II\"\n\ndef test_migration_adds_salary_range_column(db_path):\n    conn = sqlite3.connect(str(db_path))\n    conn.execute(\"\"\"CREATE TABLE jobs (key TEXT PRIMARY KEY, source TEXT, company TEXT,\n        external_id TEXT, title TEXT, url TEXT, location TEXT, department TEXT,\n        employment_type TEXT, posted_at TEXT, content_hash TEXT,\n        first_seen TEXT, last_seen TEXT)\"\"\")\n    conn.commit(); conn.close()\n    store = Store(db_path)  # must not raise\n    cols = {r[\"name\"] for r in store.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA table_info(jobs)\")}\n    assert \"salary_range\" in cols\n    store.close()\n\ndef test_meta_roundtrip_and_upsert(db_path):\n    with Store(db_path) as store:\n        assert store.get_meta(\"k\") is None\n        store.set_meta(\"k\", \"v1\")\n        store.set_meta(\"k\", \"v2\")\n        assert store.get_meta(\"k\") == \"v2\"\n\ndef test_next_seq_increments(db_path):\n    with Store(db_path) as store:\n        assert store.next_seq(\"c\") == 1\n        assert store.next_seq(\"c\") == 2\n        assert store.next_seq(\"c\") == 3\n\ndef test_next_seq_concurrent_callers_never_collide(db_path):\n    # Regression test for the parallel-worker collision class of bugs.\n    Store(db_path).close()  # create schema first\n    results = []\n    lock = threading.Lock()\n\n    def worker():\n        s = Store(db_path)\n        n = s.next_seq(\"report_seq\")\n        with lock:\n            results.append(n)\n        s.close()\n\n    threads = [threading.Thread(target=worker) for _ in range(20)]\n    for t in threads: t.start()\n    for t in threads: t.join()\n    assert sorted(results) == list(range(1, 21))  # no duplicates, no gaps\n\ndef test_added_since_is_strictly_greater_than(db_path):\n    with Store(db_path) as store:\n        store.diff([_job()])\n        ts = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT first_seen FROM jobs\").fetchone()[0]\n        assert store.added_since(ts) == []  # strict >, not >=\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `fetchers.py` — the largest untested surface\n\nThis file has ~20 `parse_*` pure functions (each with defensive/positional field access worth locking down) and ~15 `fetch_*` async functions that need `httpx.MockTransport`. Given the size, prioritize:\n\n**A. Pure parsers — high value, cheap to write.** Pattern to replicate across every `parse_*`:\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_parsers.py\nfrom fetchers import (parse_greenhouse, parse_lever, _lever_salary, parse_ashby,\n                       parse_google, _ds1_posted_at, parse_deshaw, parse_apple,\n                       _apple_posted_at, parse_amazon, _amazon_posted_at,\n                       _balanced_json, _bd_location, parse_bytedance)\n\ndef test_parse_greenhouse_maps_fields():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": 1, \"title\": \"SWE\", \"absolute_url\": \"https://x\",\n                       \"location\": {\"name\": \"NYC\"},\n                       \"departments\": [{\"name\": \"Eng\"}, {\"name\": \"Infra\"}],\n                       \"updated_at\": \"2024-01-01\"}]}\n    [j] = parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", data)\n    assert j.department == \"Eng, Infra\"\n    assert j.external_id == \"1\"\n\ndef test_parse_greenhouse_empty_jobs_list():\n    assert parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", {\"jobs\": []}) == []\n\ndef test_parse_greenhouse_missing_jobs_key():\n    assert parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", {}) == []\n\ndef test_lever_salary_with_range():\n    assert _lever_salary({\"salaryRange\": {\"min\": 100000, \"max\": 150000, \"currency\": \"USD\"}}) \\\n        == \"USD 100,000–150,000\"\n\ndef test_lever_salary_falls_back_to_description():\n    assert _lever_salary({\"salaryDescriptionPlain\": \"Competitive\"}) == \"Competitive\"\n\ndef test_lever_salary_missing_entirely():\n    assert _lever_salary({}) == \"\"\n\ndef test_parse_ashby_skips_unlisted():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": \"1\", \"isListed\": False, \"title\": \"Hidden\"},\n                      {\"id\": \"2\", \"isListed\": True, \"title\": \"Visible\"}]}\n    out = parse_ashby(\"acme\", data)\n    assert len(out) == 1 and out[0].external_id == \"2\"\n\ndef test_balanced_json_extracts_nested_object():\n    text = 'prefix {\"a\": {\"b\": 1}, \"c\": \"}\"} suffix'\n    assert _balanced_json(text, text.index(\"{\")) == '{\"a\": {\"b\": 1}, \"c\": \"}\"}'\n\ndef test_balanced_json_unbalanced_returns_none():\n    assert _balanced_json('{\"a\": 1', 0) is None\n\ndef test_ds1_posted_at_prefers_create_time_index_12():\n    job = [None]*13\n    job[12] = [1700000000, 0]\n    job[13] = [1800000000, 0]\n    assert _ds1_posted_at(job) != \"\"\n    from datetime import datetime, timezone\n    assert _ds1_posted_at(job) == datetime.fromtimestamp(1700000000, timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n\ndef test_ds1_posted_at_falls_back_when_index_12_empty():\n    job = [None]*15\n    job[13] = [1700000000, 0]\n    assert _ds1_posted_at(job) != \"\"\n\ndef test_ds1_posted_at_no_timestamps_returns_empty():\n    assert _ds1_posted_at([None]*20) == \"\"\n\ndef test_apple_posted_at_trims_nanoseconds():\n    assert _apple_posted_at(\"2024-01-15T10:00:03.812668311Z\") == \"2024-01-15T10:00:03.812668+00:00\"\n\ndef test_apple_posted_at_empty_input():\n    assert _apple_posted_at(\"\") == \"\"\n    assert _apple_posted_at(None) == \"\"\n\ndef test_amazon_posted_at_parses_us_date():\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"June 26, 2026\") == \"2026-06-26T00:00:00+00:00\"\n\ndef test_amazon_posted_at_unparseable_returns_empty():\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"\") == \"\"\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"garbage\") == \"\"\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"Frobtember 1, 2024\") == \"\"  # bad month name -> KeyError caught\n\ndef test_bd_location_walks_parent_chain():\n    city = {\"en_name\": \"SF\", \"parent\": {\"en_name\": \"CA\", \"parent\": {\"en_name\": \"US\"}}}\n    assert _bd_location(city) == \"SF, CA, US\"\n\ndef test_bd_location_none_returns_empty():\n    assert _bd_location(None) == \"\"\n\ndef test_parse_deshaw_dedups_by_job_id():\n    html = 'data-job-id=\"1\" class=\"job-display-name\">Eng I<' \\\n           'data-job-id=\"1\" class=\"job-display-name\">Eng I<'\n    out = parse_deshaw(\"deshaw\", html)\n    assert len(out) == 1\n```\n\nEvery `parse_*` (`smartrecruiters`, `recruitee`, `workable`, `optiver`, `eightfold`, `phenom`, `microsoft`, `netflix`, `meta`, `twosigma`) needs the same treatment: (1) well-formed payload → correct field mapping, (2) missing/`None` optional fields don't raise, (3) empty list/dict input → `[]`. This is the single biggest coverage gap in the repo by function count.\n\n**B. `_request` retry/backoff logic** — currently completely unverified, and it's the thing standing between a flaky upstream and a broken pipeline run:\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_request.py\nimport httpx\nimport pytest\nfrom fetchers import _request\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_request_retries_on_503_then_succeeds(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"asyncio.sleep\", lambda *_: None)  # skip real backoff\n    calls = {\"n\": 0}\n    def handler(request):\n        calls[\"n\"] += 1\n        if calls[\"n\"] < 3:\n            return httpx.Response(503)\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"ok\": True})\n    transport = httpx.MockTransport(handler)\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=transport) as client:\n        r = await _request(client, \"https://x/test\")\n    assert r.status_code == 200\n    assert calls[\"n\"] == 3\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_request_exhausts_retries_raises(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"asyncio.sleep\", lambda *_: None)\n    transport = httpx.MockTransport(lambda r: httpx.Response(500))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=transport) as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError, match=\"failed to fetch\"):\n            await _request(client, \"https://x/test\", retries=2)\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_request_does_not_retry_on_404():\n    calls = {\"n\": 0}\n    def handler(request):\n        calls[\"n\"] += 1\n        return httpx.Response(404)\n    transport = httpx.MockTransport(handler)\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=transport) as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError):\n            await _request(client, \"https://x/test\")\n    assert calls[\"n\"] == 1  # 404 isn't in the retryable set, raise_for_status fires immediately\n```\n\n**C. `fetch_all` error isolation** — a single source failing must not kill the whole run:\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_fetch_all.py\nimport httpx, pytest\nfrom fetchers import fetch_all\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_all_isolates_failures(monkeypatch, capsys):\n    def handler(request):\n        if \"broken\" in str(request.url):\n            return httpx.Response(500)\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"jobs\": [{\"id\": 1, \"title\": \"X\",\n            \"absolute_url\": \"\", \"location\": {}, \"departments\": []}]})\n    transport = httpx.MockTransport(handler)\n    client = httpx.AsyncClient(transport=transport)\n    sources = [{\"ats\": \"greenhouse\", \"company\": \"broken\"},\n               {\"ats\": \"greenhouse\", \"company\": \"ok\"}]\n    jobs = await fetch_all(sources, client=client, concurrency=2)\n    await client.aclose()\n    assert len(jobs) == 1\n    assert \"! greenhouse:broken failed\" in capsys.readouterr().out\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_source_unknown_ats_raises():\n    from fetchers import fetch_source\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"unknown ATS\"):\n        await fetch_source(None, {\"ats\": \"bogus\"})\n```\n\n**D. Pagination stop conditions** (`fetch_optiver`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_eightfold`, `fetch_bytedance`, `fetch_apple`, `fetch_google`) — each has slightly different \"stop paginating\" logic (empty fresh batch, dedup-by-`external_id`, `max_pages` cap, or a `total`/`count` check). At minimum, test one representative fetcher for: (1) stops when a page returns no new items, (2) respects `max_pages`, (3) dedupes across pages when the API returns overlapping results. `fetch_google`'s `_extract_ds1` regex-based extraction is especially fragile (site-layout-shift risk) and deserves its own malformed-HTML test (missing `ds:1` key → `[]`, not a crash).\n\n**E. `fetch_ashby`'s fallback path** (posting-api 404 → hosted-page HTML scrape) is a distinct code path from the happy path and is entirely untested — needs a mocked 404 + a mocked HTML page with `window.__appData`.\n\n---\n\n### 5. `notify.py` — notifiers + `dispatch`\n\n**Gaps:**\n- Each notifier's env-var gating: absent env var → no-op, no network call attempted (verify via `monkeypatch.delenv` + asserting no httpx call).\n- Each notifier's \"nothing to report\" short-circuit (`not (new or changed)`).\n- `dispatch()`'s exception isolation — **currently the single most important untested behavior in this file**: if `notify_slack` raises (e.g., bad webhook), `notify_email`/`notify_sms` must still run. There's no test proving this.\n- `_sms_body`: truncation at `limit`, ASCII-only content (no `•`/`…`), `\"+N more\"` suffix.\n- `notify_sms`: `raise_for_status()` propagates on Twilio failure (and `dispatch` must swallow it, per above).\n\n```python\n# tests/test_notify.py\nimport httpx\nimport pytest\nfrom models import Job\nfrom notify import dispatch, notify_slack, notify_sms, _sms_body\n\ndef _job(title=\"Eng\"):\n    return Job(source=\"gh\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=title, url=\"https://x\")\n\ndef test_slack_noop_without_env_var(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.delenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", raising=False)\n    calls = []\n    monkeypatch.setattr(httpx, \"post\", lambda *a, **k: calls.append(1))\n    notify_slack([_job()], [])\n    assert calls == []\n\ndef test_slack_noop_when_nothing_new(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks.slack/x\")\n    calls = []\n    monkeypatch.setattr(httpx, \"post\", lambda *a, **k: calls.append(1))\n    notify_slack([], [])\n    assert calls == []\n\ndef test_dispatch_isolates_notifier_failures(monkeypatch, capsys):\n    def boom(new, changed): raise RuntimeError(\"bad webhook\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"notify.NOTIFIERS\", [boom, lambda n, c: print(\"second ran\")])\n    dispatch([_job()], [])\n    out = capsys.readouterr().out\n    assert \"second ran\" in out\n    assert \"! boom failed\" in out or \"! <lambda> failed\" in out\n\ndef test_sms_body_truncates_and_ascii_only():\n    jobs = [_job(f\"Role {i}\") for i in range(10)]\n    body = _sms_body(jobs, [], limit=8)\n    assert \"+2 more\" in body\n    assert all(ord(c) < 128 for c in body)\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"missing_var\", [\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\", \"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\",\n                                          \"TWILIO_FROM\", \"TWILIO_TO\"])\ndef test_sms_requires_all_four_env_vars(monkeypatch, missing_var):\n    for v in (\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\", \"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\", \"TWILIO_FROM\", \"TWILIO_TO\"):\n        monkeypatch.setenv(v, \"x\")\n    monkeypatch.delenv(missing_var, raising=False)\n    calls = []\n    monkeypatch.setattr(httpx, \"post\", lambda *a, **k: calls.append(1))\n    notify_sms([_job()], [])\n    assert calls == []\n```\n\n---\n\n### 6. `pipeline.py` — `load_config`, `run`\n\n**Gaps:**\n- `load_config` default-filling (`sources`, `filters`, `db`, `concurrency` all get defaults when absent from YAML).\n- `run(dry_run=True)` — does not touch `Store`, returns `new=0, changed=0`, doesn't call `dispatch`.\n- `run(dry_run=False)` — full path: `fetch_all` → `filter_jobs` → `Store.diff` → `dispatch` → return dict shape.\n- Integration gap: no end-to-end test wiring a fake source through the whole pipeline into a temp DB.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_pipeline.py\nimport pytest\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom pipeline import load_config, run\n\ndef test_load_config_fills_defaults(tmp_path):\n    cfg_file = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg_file.write_text(\"sources: []\\n\")\n    cfg = load_config(cfg_file)\n    assert cfg[\"filters\"] == {}\n    assert cfg[\"db\"] == \"jobs.db\"\n    assert cfg[\"concurrency\"] == 8\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_run_dry_run_does_not_persist(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    cfg_file = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg_file.write_text(f\"sources: []\\nfilters: {{}}\\ndb: {tmp_path/'jobs.db'}\\n\")\n    result = await run(cfg_file, dry_run=True)\n    assert result == {\"matched\": 0, \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}\n    assert not (tmp_path / \"jobs.db\").exists()\n```\n\nAn integration test that stubs `fetch_all` to return a couple of `Job`s and asserts they land in `Store`, plus that `dispatch` was invoked, would close the biggest end-to-end gap — right now not a single test exercises more than one module at a time.\n\n---\n\n### 7. `agent.py` — CLI subcommands + PDF rendering\n\n**Gaps:**\n- `cmd_db_new`: first-run window (`since_days`) vs. marker-based window; `--posted-days` filtering (dropped/kept/undated counters); `--dated-only`; group-boundary truncation logic (the `groupby`-based truncate-at-batch-boundary is subtle and has zero coverage — a bug here would silently split or duplicate a batch).\n- `cmd_db_mark`: `--now`, explicit ISO watermark, invalid-timestamp rejection (exit code 2), neither-arg-given rejection.\n- `cmd_report_num`: delegates to `Store.next_seq`, zero-padded output format.\n- `_normalize_ats`: the character-replacement table — critically, **must not touch text inside `<style>`/`<script>`/tag attributes**, only body text between tags. This is exactly the kind of regex-based logic that silently breaks on edge cases (e.g., a smart quote inside an `alt=\"...\"` attribute).\n- `_chrome_bin`: `CHROME_PATH` env override, `shutil.which` discovery, hardcoded macOS app paths, exits when none found.\n- `cmd_pdf_render`: missing input file (exit 2), successful PDF byte-signature check, failure path when Chrome doesn't produce a valid `%PDF` header.\n- `main()`'s argv dispatch logic (mode-word vs. flag boundary detection) — untested branching that determines `run_claude` args.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_agent.py\nimport pytest\nfrom agent import cmd_db_mark, _normalize_ats, main\n\ndef test_db_mark_rejects_invalid_timestamp(capsys):\n    rc = cmd_db_mark([\"not-a-date\"])\n    assert rc == 2\n    assert \"not an ISO timestamp\" in capsys.readouterr().err\n\ndef test_db_mark_requires_watermark_or_now(capsys):\n    rc = cmd_db_mark([])\n    assert rc == 2\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_replaces_body_text_only():\n    html = '<style>content: \"\\u2014\";</style><p>em\\u2014dash</p>'\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n    assert 'content: \"\\u2014\"' in out  # untouched inside <style>\n    assert \"em-dash\" in out            # replaced in body\n    assert counts[\"em-dash\"] == 1\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_does_not_touch_tag_attributes():\n    html = '<a title=\"quote\\u2019s\">text</a>'\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n    assert 'title=\"quote\\u2019s\"' in out  # attribute preserved\n    assert counts == {}\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_counts_multiple_replacement_types():\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(\"<p>a\\u2014b \\u201Cquoted\\u201D c\\u2026</p>\")\n    assert counts[\"em-dash\"] == 1\n    assert counts[\"smart-double-quote\"] == 2\n    assert counts[\"ellipsis\"] == 1\n\ndef test_main_help_flag(capsys):\n    rc = main.__wrapped__([\"-h\"]) if hasattr(main, \"__wrapped__\") else None\n    # or invoke via subprocess if main() reads sys.argv directly\n```\n\n(`main()` reads `sys.argv` directly rather than taking an `argv` param, so testing it cleanly requires either a small refactor to accept `argv` — recommended — or `monkeypatch.setattr(sys, \"argv\", [...])` + capturing `SystemExit`/return code.)\n\nFor `cmd_db_new`'s truncation logic specifically:\n\n```python\ndef test_db_new_truncates_at_group_boundary_not_mid_group(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    # Build a store with two first_seen groups of 3 rows each, limit=4.\n    # Assert the dump contains exactly 3 rows (first full group only),\n    # watermark == first group's timestamp — proves it never splits a group.\n    ...\n```\n\n---\n\n### Priority ranking\n\n| Priority | Area | Why |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | `store.py` `next_seq` / `diff` concurrency | Matches a bug class you've already hit (`jobsquare-parallel-worker-collisions` memory) |\n| P0 | `notify.py` `dispatch` error isolation | One bad webhook currently *could* silently kill SMS/email if isolation regresses |\n| P1 | `fetchers.py` parse_* functions (all ~20) | Largest function count, zero coverage, each ATS has undocumented/positional payload quirks that silently degrade |\n| P1 | `models.py` `parse_posted_at` / `content_hash` | Feeds dedup and recency filtering across the whole pipeline |\n| P2 | `fetchers.py` `_request` retry/backoff | Currently unverified; a regression here turns transient errors into hard failures |\n| P2 | `agent.py` `cmd_db_new` truncation | Subtle group-boundary logic with no test proving it doesn't split/duplicate |\n| P3 | `pipeline.py` end-to-end integration | No test currently exercises more than one module together |\n| P3 | `agent.py` `_normalize_ats` / `_chrome_bin` / PDF render | Lower risk (visual output), but the tag-vs-body regex split is exactly the kind of thing that silently breaks |\n\nWant me to scaffold `tests/` with these skeletons as real files (plus a `pytest`/`pytest-asyncio` addition to `requirements.txt`) so they're runnable rather than just illustrative?\n",
